---
import Page from "../layouts/Page.astro"
import HeroCard from "../components/HeroCard.astro"
import InstallCard from "../components/InstallCard.astro"

const title = "agentimization — geo audit for agent-ready websites"
const description =
  "one command to score how well ai agents can discover, parse, and cite your site. 36 checks, a 0 to 100 grade, and ready-to-paste fixes."

const jsonLd = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebSite",
    name: "agentimization",
    url: "https://agentimization.com",
    description,
    author: { "@type": "Person", name: "Anthony Lio" },
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "SoftwareApplication",
    name: "agentimization",
    applicationCategory: "DeveloperApplication",
    operatingSystem: "macOS, Linux, Windows",
    offers: { "@type": "Offer", price: "0", priceCurrency: "USD" },
    softwareVersion: "0.1.0",
    downloadUrl: "https://www.npmjs.com/package/agentimization",
    author: { "@type": "Person", name: "Anthony Lio" },
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    mainEntity: [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        name: "What is GEO?",
        acceptedAnswer: {
          "@type": "Answer",
          text: "Generative engine optimization. The set of practices that make a website discoverable, parseable, and citable by ai agents like Claude, ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Gemini.",
        },
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        name: "What does agentimization actually check?",
        acceptedAnswer: {
          "@type": "Answer",
          text: "36 checks across 8 categories: content discoverability, markdown availability, content structure, page size and rendering, url stability, authentication, geo signals, and agent protocols.",
        },
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        name: "Does it work on local directories too?",
        acceptedAnswer: {
          "@type": "Answer",
          text: "Yes. Pass a path instead of a url and it audits the files on disk. Useful as a ci pre-deploy step.",
        },
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        name: "How is the score computed?",
        acceptedAnswer: {
          "@type": "Answer",
          text: "Each check returns pass, warn, fail, or skip. Checks are weighted by impact. The weighted average becomes a 0 to 100 score, mapped to a letter grade. A failing auth gate caps the overall score at 50.",
        },
      },
    ],
  },
]
---

<Page title={title} description={description} path="/" jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <HeroCard />

  <h1>geo audit for agent-ready websites.</h1>
  <p class="byline">
    by <a href="https://antl.io" rel="author">anthony lio</a> &middot;
    <time datetime="2026-04-29">apr 29, 2026</time> &middot;
    updated <time datetime="2026-05-02">may 2, 2026</time>
  </p>
  <p>
    one command to score how well ai agents can discover, parse, and cite your
    site. 36 checks, a 0 to 100 grade, and ready-to-paste fixes for whatever's
    broken.
  </p>

  <InstallCard />

  <h2>how it works</h2>
  <p>
    point it at any url. it samples up to 10 pages, runs 36 checks against the
    html, headers, and well-known files, then weights them into a single score.
    every failure comes with a suggestion you can paste straight into <span class="pill">claude code</span>,
    cursor, or any ai agent that can edit your repo.
  </p>

  <h2>by the numbers</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>36 checks</strong> across <strong>8 categories</strong>. samples up to
    <strong>10 pages</strong> per audit. a typical run completes in <strong>under
    15 seconds</strong>. weights map a 0 to 100 score to one of six grade bands.
  </p>

  <h2>terminology</h2>
  <p>
    <dfn><strong>geo</strong></dfn> is a name for the practices that make a
    website discoverable by ai agents. <dfn><strong>llms.txt</strong></dfn>
    refers to a small text file at the root of a site that lists key pages and
    their purpose. <dfn><strong>content negotiation</strong></dfn> means a
    server returns different formats (html or markdown) based on the request's
    <code>Accept</code> header. <dfn><strong>e-e-a-t</strong></dfn> stands for
    experience, expertise, authoritativeness, and trustworthiness, the signals
    generative engines use to decide what's safe to cite. read the
    <a href="/about">about page</a> for the longer explanation, the
    <a href="/about#how-the-score-works">scoring rubric</a>, or the
    <a href="https://github.com/antlio/agentimization">source repository</a>
    for more.
  </p>

  <h2>what it checks</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>content discoverability</strong> &nbsp;<code>llms.txt</code>, sitemap, robots</li>
    <li><strong>markdown availability</strong> &nbsp;<code>.md</code> urls, content negotiation</li>
    <li><strong>content structure</strong> &nbsp;headings, code fences, hidden tabs</li>
    <li><strong>page size and rendering</strong> &nbsp;ssr vs csr, boilerplate ratio</li>
    <li><strong>url stability</strong> &nbsp;status codes, redirects, canonicals</li>
    <li><strong>authentication and access</strong> &nbsp;gates, alternative paths</li>
    <li><strong>geo signals</strong> &nbsp;json-ld, citations, freshness, e-e-a-t</li>
    <li><strong>agent protocols</strong> &nbsp;mcp card, api catalog, agents.md, link headers</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>programmatic use</h2>
  <pre><code>{`import { audit } from "@agentimization/core"

const result = await audit("https://your-site.com")
console.log(result.grade, result.overall_score)`}</code></pre>

  <h2>faq</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>what is geo?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>
          generative engine optimization. the set of practices that make a
          website discoverable, parseable, and citable by ai agents like claude,
          chatgpt, perplexity, and gemini.
        </p>
        <p>
          it overlaps with seo but the audience is different. seo optimizes for
          ranking algorithms. geo optimizes for systems that read your content,
          summarize it, and decide whether to cite you.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>does it work on local directories too?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>
          yes. pass a path instead of a url and it audits the files on disk.
          useful as a ci pre-deploy step.
        </p>
        <pre><code>agentimization . --json</code></pre>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>how is the score computed?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>
          each check returns pass, warn, fail, or skip. checks are weighted by
          impact. the weighted average becomes a 0 to 100 score, mapped to a
          letter grade.
        </p>
        <p>a failing auth gate caps the overall score at 50, since agents that cannot reach your content cannot read it.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>what's an example fix?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>
          if you fail <code>llms-txt-exists</code>, the suggestion is a copy-paste-ready
          markdown skeleton with your project's title, blockquote description,
          and section headings linking to your key pages.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>can i hide it from a category?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>
          yes. pass <code>--category content-discoverability</code> to only run that one
          group, or set <code>categories</code> in the programmatic api.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <h2>more</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/about">about agentimization</a> — the longer write-up</li>
    <li><a href="/about#how-the-score-works">how the score works</a> — the scoring rubric in detail</li>
    <li><a href="/index.md">this page in markdown</a> — paste straight into an agent</li>
    <li><a href="/llms.txt">llms.txt</a> — site index for ai agents</li>
    <li><a href="/llms-full.txt">llms-full.txt</a> — full content as plain text</li>
  </ul>
</Page>
